English

[edit]
English Wikipedia has an article on:
Winter
Wikipedia

Alternative forms

[edit]
  • (surname): Wintour

Proper noun

[edit]

Winter (countable and uncountable, plural Winters)

  1. (countable) A surname from the Germanic languages.
  2. (countable) A unisex given name.
  3. A placename:
    1. An unincorporated community in the Rural Municipality of Senlac, No. 411, Saskatchewan, Canada.
    2. An unincorporated community in Putnam County, West Virginia, United States.
    3. A small town and village in Sawyer County, Wisconsin, United States.
  4. The personification of winter, wintertime.

Derived terms

[edit]
  • Winter's bark (Drimys winteri)
  • Winter's law

Noun

[edit]

Winter (countable and uncountable, plural Winters)

  1. (poetry) Alternative letter-case form of winter.

German

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From Middle High German winder, winter, from Old High German wintar, from Proto-West Germanic *wintru, from Proto-Germanic *wintruz. Compare Dutch winter, English winter, Danish vinter.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /ˈvɪntɐ/
  • Audio:(file)
  • Audio (Germany (Berlin)):(file)

Noun

[edit]

Winter m (strong, genitive Winters, plural Winter)

  1. winter

Declension

Hunsrik

[edit]

Alternative forms

[edit]
  • winter (Wiesemann spelling)

Etymology

[edit]

    Inherited from Central Franconian Wenter, from Middle High German winter, from Old High German wintar, from Proto-West Germanic *wintru, from Proto-Germanic *wintruz.[1]

    Pronunciation

    [edit]
    • IPA(key): /ˈvinta/
    • Rhymes: -inta
    • Syllabification: Win‧ter

    Noun

    [edit]

    Winter m (plural Winter)

    1. winter
      Im Winter werd-s aarich kalt.
      In winter it gets very cold.

    Related terms

    [edit]
    • Winterschnees

    See also

    [edit]
    Seasons in Hunsrik · Johreszeide (layout · text) · category
    Frihjoher, Frihling (“spring”) Sommer, Summer (“summer”) Herrebst (“autumn”) Winter (“winter”)

    References

    [edit]
    1. ^ Boll, Piter Kehoma (2021), “Winter”, in Dicionário Hunsriqueano Riograndense–Português, 3rd edition (overall work in Portuguese), Ivoti: Riograndenser Hunsrickisch, page 176, column 2
